Who We Are

Built on Relationship,
Rooted in Community

Recognizing the need for community-driven initiatives, we formed Rock Gap Kinship to counter stereotypes and uplift racialized and marginalized groups by highlighting their strengths, creativity, and innovation.

We focus on supporting communities to overcome challenges and advocate for improved services and support systems in ways that honor and respect diverse cultures and histories. We work closely with partners to provide valuable guidance on facilitation, mobilization, data analysis, and sharing information with the public.

Our goal is to create long-lasting positive impacts by amplifying voices that have historically been marginalized.

Our Approach

Moving Toward
Equity Together

Moving together toward equity in capacity building requires adaptive teaching and learning styles. We acknowledge, deconstruct, and transform from Western systems to nation building with communities.

We center collaboration to help create policies and practices that address unconscious bias and internalized oppression, promote equitable opportunities, and ensure representation at all levels.

01

Capacity & Nation Building

We center collaboration to help create policies and practices that address unconscious bias, promote equitable opportunities, and ensure representation at all levels of community life.

02

Community Engagement

Connected to Black and Native American communities, we build meaningful relationships and facilitate effective engagement strategies for organizations seeking to collaborate authentically.

03

Lived Experience & Advocacy

Lived experience is an asset. Paired with social work training, we help organizations develop more responsive, equitable practices while advocating for systemic change and social justice.

Black & Native American Storytelling

A Space to Re-Imagine the Work

RGK is rooted in Black and Native American Storytelling approaches to create safe spaces that amplify voices — shedding light on challenges, triumphs, and contributions.

We embrace alternative forms of knowledge sharing that honors communities and decolonizes academic research practices. By weaving these narratives through creative means, we help create an accurate understanding of these communities, foster empathy, and promote social change.

Storytelling has the power to empower people and communities. This sharing process can be healing and foster a sense of belonging — validating the experience of every person we serve.

Images are an extension of storytelling. We work collectively with community to dismantle oppressive systems and elevate the stories of our kin.
Our Team

The People Behind the Work

Serena Denetsosie
MSW · Co-Founder

A passionate advocate for humanity and equity, Serena embodies the essence of K’é, drawing strength from her identity as a Diné (Navajo) woman. Her connection to her traditional ways informs every aspect of her work and interactions.

Serena’s unwavering commitment to nurturing authentic relationships and valuing people above all else forms the foundation of her collaborative approach. Her strategic mindset in identifying core challenges enables her to navigate with purpose toward the well-being of every community she engages with.

Member of the Rock Gap Clan, born for the Towering House Clan · Maternal clan: Bitter Water · Paternal clan: Yucca Fruit Strung Out in a Line
Cynthia Mackey
MSW · Co-Founder

A Black mixed-race Canadian, Cindy possesses a remarkable talent for nurturing spaces where individuals feel free to be their true selves. She exudes grace, compassion, and intentionality — adept at dismantling exclusive practices entrenched in Western systems.

Cindy’s creativity is a standout quality as she strives to curate content that highlights the uniqueness of individuals, communities, and projects — empowering others to express their needs and voices respectfully, allowing for more accurate representation of community.

Heart-centered leader · Community advocate · Devoted to fostering authentic collaboration and reclaiming community narratives
